animal.description:
Sweet, shy Noel. This little darling really needs nothing more than a warm bed, a snuggly lap and some nifty treats in her life. She aims to please and would do well with a quiet family. She's a 2 year old shepherd mix and around 31 pounds. She gets along with her buds on the farm but is perfectly happy on her own. A fam with another like-minded pup would be a fun companion for her to help her build her confidence. One look into those gorgeous eyes of hers and you'll be smitten, and those ears, tho! She's really the total package of cute, fun and snuggles. With some reassurance from her loving, new family, Noel will blossom into the forever companion you've been waiting for.

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Meet Raven!

My name is Raven. Let me tell you a little about myself and how I'm looking for my new family. I am 9.5 years old and weigh 50 pounds. I know I'm not a puppy but I can do anything a puppy can do but even better. I'm housetrained. I know how to cuddle and give lots of love and kisses. I know that I should be good and I do that pretty well. I get along with other dogs, and even kids! I love blankets and sleeping. Who doesn't like a good nap?

My muzzle has turned a little gray but I think I look beautiful and distinguished. I have beautiful short brindle fur. So how did I end up in up in foster care you ask?? Well, my previous parents took my brother and I to our veterinarian clinic for boarding back in November 2020 and never came back for us. My brother left back in December to go to a German Shepard rescue and I bet he found a new home already. I don't know why our parents gave us up. We were good dogs. I guess they didn't love us as much as we loved them. So if anyone wants a loving lady, I'm your girl. I'm ready to be all yours! 

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
This curly boy is Dudley, he was found as a stray running in and out of traffic on a freeway ramp in Indy. Dudley has been in his foster home for a bit now getting vetted and learning some manners while we learned about him

Here is Dudley's foster's input:

 Will need a home with other dogs. He has a very high "play" drive. He has done well with the other two dogs in his foster home (plays for hours).

 Okay with cats. He has been around the fosters cat with interest but without issue.

 Food motivated/not food aggressive.

 High energy. Fenced yard required. Does frequent "zoomies" in the house.

 Busy. He checks everything out with his nose. Has a fetish for fabrics. Loves to steal/play with gloves, socks, small rags, etc.

 Crate trained. Sleeps well in crate at night.

 Tolerates time at home alone. Did well confined to the kitchen when the foster was gone for large periods of the day over 2 weeks with no accidents or damage.

 Trainable. Demonstrated greatly improved walking on leash with introduction of 3 in 1 harness. Responds to "sit" and "off" working on "down."

 Loves to be near his people. Follows people around (closely) and wants to be in the same room with them.

 Would need a home with no/older children. He grabs sleeves or the back of pant legs to get human attention and will need further training to stop this.

 Is "somewhat" housebroken. Still learning and has an accident here and there.

 Neutered, has shots, negative for heart worm. He has had Rabies, DAPP, Bordetella and he tested negative on 4DX Snap Test

 Weight: 27 lbs (approximately)

 Age: 1 year (based on several estimates) - very, very much still a puppy

 Escapes: Dudley is a "runner" and regularly checks the gate at the fosters house to see if he can head out for some freedom in the neighborhood.

 Car rides: tolerates well

 Must be experienced with very active dogs - absolutely not a first time dog owner

 Training - must be very capable of training/willing to take to training class and consistently reinforce (otherwise "Dudley will train you)

We require that you have a fenced in yard, not a "kennel" in the yard AND we do not approve underground fencing. Depending upon the dog some exceptions are made for those who live in apartments. We also require that the adoptee will be a part of the family "living" within the home. Our adoption process may be found on our website at www.bitofheaven.org

Visits are scheduled by appointment only via emailing request to ownedbycaninesandlovit@yahoo.com

animal.description: Meet sweet mama Darla! She is around 2 years old and is likely a mix of many breeds, but may have Pit Bull Terrier and Whippet in her. She is petite at only about 30 lbs. Darla came to Labs and More with her 9 puppies who are now around 2 months old. Darla is ready to put parenthood behind her and get the TLC she needs. Darla is a shy girl who seems to warm up to women faster than men. She is looking for a kind and patient family that will help her work on her confidence and come out of her shell. For that reason, she would do best in a quieter home at this time. Once she trusts you, she is a sweetheart who enjoys receiving attention. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Darla, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. animal.description:
Meet Cheech! Cheech is a very big, goofy boy! He was dumped on a good Samaritan who would have loved to keep him, but could not keep another dog. Cheech has lived with kids of all ages and loved to have someone to protect - he can be excitable and will knock over young kids on accident. He got along well with the other dogs in the home. He does well on car rides and enjoys them once he realizes what is going on. He loves to play tug-of-war and his favorite toys are the ropes. 
Cheech has successfully gotten over a regular 4ft chainlink fence, and will require something more secure to keep him safe! He is house-trained and will go to the door to let you know if he has to potty! 
Cheech is neutered, microchipped, and up to date on all shots. He is a very large boy weighing in at approximately 80 pounds. His estimated date of birth is 4/15/19....All pets have lifetime sanctuary at Haven of the Ozarks. If they cannot remain with their adopter, they must be returned to the Haven.

Adoption fees are as follows: 
Puppies under the age of 6 months - $125
Dogs weighing 30 pounds and less - $125

animal.description:
Hi everyone! My name is Cherish! I am a 1-year-old American Staffordshire Terroir. I'm the cutest little girl you'll ever see. I'm small, friendly, and my coat is super duper soft! I just arrived from a shelter in North Carolina, so the caretakers here are still getting to know me. They know that I'm super nice and am sure to be a snuggle bug once I'm in a home with a soft couch. Doesn't that sounds nice?! I loooove running around the yard. When I get the zoomies, my floppy ears fly back and my big cheeks bounce up and down while I run! They also learned that I could use a little practice with some basic manners. When I'm excited I can't help but jump! It's cute, but a bit inappropriate. But I'm so young, I'm sure I can catch on to any training you want with a few good practices! I'm not sure how I would deal with another dog in my face just yet, but I do OK in the kennels with dogs being moved in front of me. I'm also not too sure about cats or kids yet. Have a conversation with the staff to learn more. If I seem like a good fit for you, stop into Stray Haven and we can hang out for a bit! See you soon!

animal.description:
Hello! Halo here, a 1-and-a-half-year-old Catahoula Leopard Dog/Boxer mix! I'm quite the looker with 1 blue eye! I have the biggest bat-like ears and the personality to match! I'm a playful little girl who just got sent up here from a shelter in North Carolina. I'm looking for a home that can tire me out, because I have some energy! Most of that energy is put toward getting attention from the people I like. I loooove getting petted! I could stand to learn some manners though when it comes to personal space. I tend to jump when I get excited. The staff here are working on it with me, but WOW I'm so happy to see them I can't help but jump! I'm not too sure how I feel about dogs, cats or kids just yet. In my previous home, I got pregnant young because they were irresponsible with me and didn't have my spayed. When my puppies were born, I was protective (of all 9!) and my human mom didn't like that. She ended up giving all my puppies away at 3 weeks of age (which was far too young) and took me to the shelter saying I was aggressive. Luckily the staff knew better and said I was a great girl, just needed some structure and some basic manners and my protective nature was simply due to my hormones. I'll be spayed before I got to my new home so there's no worry about that again! I am confident and very active so make sure you're ready for a gal like me. But I'm adorable and smaller in size and my personality is pretty endearing that I know someone will choose me and we will have a fun and great life together!

animal.description:
Kalani
Breed: Pit Bull Mix
Gender: Female
DOB: 10/23/20
Adoption Fee: $200
The Hawaiian meaning of the name Kalani is - blue sky, heavens or royal one. This heavenly Princess is going to steal your heart! She's an energetic happy puppy that's going to be a great addition to any home. Kalani would love a home with fenced yard to safely run and play in with another dog or children. Like all puppies Kalani would benefit from obedience training plus training is a great way to bond with your new dog. If you would like to meet Kalani, please fill out an adoption application and plan to fall in love!!!Please read the animal bios completely before requesting additional information as we do our best to answer the most frequently ask questions in these bios. 

In order to adopt one of our animals an application must be submitted and approved. You can find these applications by going to http://humanemorgan.org/index.php?page=adoption 

ABOUT ADOPTING FROM THE HSMC: 
The shelter address is 1170 Fairground Rd. Madison, GA 30650. For more information on any of our pets, please feel free to email us at INFO@HUMANEMORGAN.ORG give us a call at 706-343-9977. 
All dogs are heartworm negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
All cats are FeLv/FIV negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
We are open 10am-5pm Monday-Saturday, we schedule our last adoption at 4pm everyday to allow our staff enough time to feed and walk dogs. 
We are an animal shelter and therefore are not able to individually potty train our residents. Many adult dogs do arrive ""house broken"" however due to animal behavior any change in environment will make an emotional impact on the animals and therefore initiate unwanted behaviors during the acclamation period. Please keep this in mind. Puppies do not have the biological maturity to maintain absolute bladder or bowel control and will require a certain degree of potty training and house breaking. Please consider the time and commitment it takes to provide the necessary building blocks for these special babies, prior to submitting your application. 
If you have any questions please email us at info@humanemorgan.org and provide name of the animal you are interested in, in the subject line. 
Thank you, HSMC Staff 

ADOPTION FEES Adoption Fees may change without notice. Always verify the fee when finalizing the adoption. 
~ Cats and Kittens ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $100 
* 1-5 Years = $75 
* Over 5 Years = $50 
** Purebred cats and kittens may be subject to special pricing 

~ Mix Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $200 
* 1 -3 Years = $175 
* 4-8 Years = $150 
* Over 8 Years = $100

~ Purebred and Designer Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $375 
* 1-3 Years = $350 
* 4-8 Years = $275 
* Over 8 Years = $150 

~ Medical and Special Needs ~ 
We have rescued dogs and cats which require additional medical care or that have special needs which are not life threatening. In these cases we may require a higher fee to help recoup the costs of their care while at our rescue.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Boy George - a lovable and cuddly 9-month-old pup who is ready to take on the world with my future person/people. I know you'll love my long legs, little brown ""eyebrows"", and friendly personality. My foster pawrents have lots of good things to say about me - they said I am a delight and the sweetest dog! I'm housetrained and walk well on a leash. Because of COVID, I have not had the chance to meet too many other dogs, but I'm good with calmer and quieter dogs. I have a nice energy level too - I get bursts of playfulness where I like to run around the living room or play fetch but equally enjoy lounging on the couch/bed and snuggling. I will bring you a toy when I want to play which I think is pretty cute! I also have a favorite teddy bear and rope toy, both of which I like to carry around with me 

I picked up on crate-training pretty easily - I really like it when I get treats or toys to keep my mind occupied while I'm in there, like yummy stuffed Kongs. When my foster mom comes home, I will be sleeping in my crate like the good boy that I am. I love all people! I want to be friends with everyone (stranger is not a word in my vocabulary), and I also really love spending time with my own people too; my foster pawrents love how loyal I am. I'm always happy to see you when you come home (even if you have just been gone for a few minutes) and am happy to hang out with you, even if that means just spending time together cuddling on the couch. As you can see, I'm a sweet, curious, and friendly pup who is ready to bring lots of fun and love to my fur-ever home. I cannot wait to meet you!


My adoption fee is $200. This includes a spay/neuter, up-to-date vaccines, deworming, a microchip, a heartworm test, and, if needed, heartworm treatment.

animal.description:
Sky is a sweet girl who loves attention. She will seek out belly rubs every chance she gets. She also loves being outside and is eager to make friends with people or animals walking by. She hasn't displayed any aggressiveness with us and will chose to be in a room where the people are located. She is very motivated with food and treats. She does a good job in her crate but definitely appreciates being able to stretch out. 

Just a reminder, my house is a family of 4. My daughter is 13, my son almost 9. She mostly follows my husband around, when she has options. She has only peed in the house one time, otherwise she has been going to the door or even barked when she had to go out. She hasn't barked much. Her most immediately thing to train would be a solid OFF command. She does jump up on her hind legs a lot. She will try to get things off of the counters, tables, etc as soon as she can, especially if it is food related. She also doesn't care what or whom she steps on.

Otherwise, my biggest concern for her is her hip. There are many times when she will not put any weight on that leg. Physically, one can feel a difference in her hips if you just run your hands down her sides to her hind parts. Should be interesting to see what the vet has to say. 

In terms of the Foster Parent Observation Form, here's the information- 

Feeding schedule - We have been feeding her twice a day. 8 am and between 5 and 6 pm. We are giving her a half and half mixture of Earthborn Venture Alaska Polluck and Pumpkin and Earthborn Venture Smoked Turkey and Butternut Squash. Total dog food equals about 1.5 to 1.75 cups at each meal. 

Potty schedule - She seems to only be pooping once a day. Otherwise, we let her out first thing in the morning. We let her out several times during the day. We also let her out before we go to bed each night. She has only gotten us up once by barking to let her out during the night. I believe she could hold it longer during the day but here, she doesn't have to do so.

Sleep schedule - She takes several naps throughout the day. As long as she is in the room with people, she is fairly content. I believe her hip mobility severely impacts her activity levels. She is definitely more docile. We have been crating her to sleep at night. 

Likes - She hasn't taken to many toys. She loves treats and food. She will jump up and do anything to get to food and the person who has the food or treat. We don't have any other pets but she is always eager to be friends with pets who are walking by our house. We haven't socialized her with any though. So far her favorite treat is the Wellness soft well bites in the beef and turkey flavor.

Dislikes - So far she hasn't reacted to anything poorly. 

Other pertinent info - We have found it necessary for her to be in her crate for us to eat. Again, she goes into her crate easily. I usually toss a treat into her crate. Then give her another one once we have the crate securely closed. She stays there without a fuss until we are done eating and cleaning up. Then we let her back out. 

She craves attention. She is letting us do more things now that she has built up a greater level of trust, but she still craves attention. 

She also tends to fall off our ottoman (or ottoman is huge - 3 feet square) She leans or rolls and just tumbles off. We try to catch her but she is big and sometimes we aren't close enough. I am not sure if her hip can't support her or if she is just simply unaware of what she is doing. She also has a harder time going down our stairs. Again - I am sure the hip has everything to do with that. We try to keep her from going upstairs too much just because we don't want her to have issues coming down.

All in all, she is a good, sweet dog who loves to cuddle.To complete an adoption application, go to: http://almosthomeanimals.org/applications/adoption/

Rescued From: PA

Things to know about Toni:
- Toni is a snuggly, affectionate pocket pittie who's had a rough start to her life
- Toni was found by a police officer and a kind soul in Philadelphia hiding under his police car, incredibly skinny & very sick
- She was brought to ACCT but was not going to survive life in the shelter so the kind soul who found her took her in and nursed her back to health.
- She will need a confident owner with breed experience who will give her time to settle in & continue her socialization
- Despite the rough start, she has a lot of love to give to an owner who understands her needs
- Very food motivated & smart
- Learns new things very quickly
- Already knows "Sit" "Paw" & "Down"

- Low / Medium energy - Loves a walk but mostly a couch potato
- Loves squeaky toys & tennis balls
- Great at fetch
- Walks well on leash - Can be reactive to some dogs
- Loves to go for walks
- Can be mouthy when she gets really excited
- Would do best in a home with no kids for this reason
- May take a little time to warm up to new people
- Affectionate with people she knows
- Loves to snuggle
- Rides well in the car
- Housebroken
- Crate trained
- Toni will do best as the only pet in the home

animal.description:
Dog Name: Midnight 
Breed: Pitbull mix 
Sex: Male
Age: 11 months
Weight: 55lbs
Medical Needs: none


Housebroken: Yes-rings bells on doorknob 
Crate trained:Yes
Good in the car: Yes
Good on a leash: Yes


Energy level: medium/high
Need a fenced in yard: not necessarily 


Dog Friendly: Yes but hes had limited interaction with other dogs.
If yes, does your foster need another dog in its adoptive homes? I think he would love a buddy, but doesn't need one 

Cat Friendly? Yes. Lived with 3 cats

Kid Friendly: 
Not yet tested by me but did live in a home with a 4 year old 
If yes, what's the youngest child you'd recommend they be placed with? 4 years old

Special traits that make your foster special or that we need to know about them? 
Midnight was surrendered this week. He does not have vision in his left eye due to an injury from a cat. He has adapted quite well. He is very well behaved and has many good habits already in place. Chasing a ball is his fav activity. 
He has a slight personal space issue which can be endearing but not always- he thinks hes a lap dog and dives right onto your lap or chair so were working on boundaries.
He is a joy to foster and a happy boy.

animal.description:
Dena
Female
Age: 7 years old
Weight: 55lbs
Breed: Pitbull mix

Hey there, Im Dena! I am the happiest most excited girl when I get to see my human; I just wiggle all over! Speaking of getting excited, I must admit I love humans so much! In fact, I even get excited when new friends come over to meet me! I would do best in a home with older children because I can get overly excited and sometimes try to jump for kisses and would hate to hurt a smaller human!
I enjoy going on walks and think I do a great job walking on a leash. After my walks, I curl up for a good nap. I am a pretty chill girl who would love someone who is up for a good snuggle in the evenings while we watch some Netflix; peanut butter filled Kongs and tummy rubs are encouraged! I know the command, sit and am working on learning more commands! I am house trained and crate trained; I will go right into my crate and sometimes will relax there for fun! I get a little nervous when my people leave and will whine for a bit. My foster family is helping me learn that they will return soon, but for his reason, I would do best in a house as opposed to an apartment setting. Speaking of my perfect home, I would love to be an only dog. That way I would not need to share any of the amazing attention I would receive! I mean, I would not mind sharing a home with another chill fur brother, but no other ladies for me. I would certainly need to meet my potential fur sibling before finding my forever home to ensure we would be best buds for life! I really enjoy walking around my fenced in yard, but if you play with me enough, I do not think I would need a fence in my forever home.

I think my perfect family is out there for me, I just know it!

If you are interested in meeting the wiggly, Dena, apply to adopt at www.causeforcanines.org Adoption fee is $250
Children must be 11 years old or older
Must be an Ohio resident 25 years old or older
No cats or small dogs

animal.description: Ahhhh, cookies. You know what is fascinating about cookies? There is something for everyone! If you have a sweet tooth you could eat a classic chocolate chip cookie! If you like to keep it basic, a sugar cookie is an excellent option. If you want to keep it healthy, try and oatmeal raisin cookie! So. Many. Options! I'd like to think I'm like a cookie. Everyone can love me! I'm a silly girl and I have energy...But I'd also love to cuddle if you're a couch potato. If you're interested in me, please fill out an application at CHAadopt.org! (Also check out my bestie Cotton. I LOVE HER! The shelter people let us cuddle sometime)All cats and dogs adopted from the Chequamegon Humane Association are spayed or neutered, up-to-date on age appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, and microchipped. Dogs are tested for heartworm and cats are tested for FeLV/FIV (results negative unless otherwise noted). A tax-deductible adoption fee of $150 is required for adult dogs, puppies are $200, and dogs over the age of 10 are $85. Adult cat adoption fees are $50, kittens under one year are $90, and cats over the age of 10 are $35.

animal.description:
Flower is a lovable little mixed breed puppy. Her momma was pulled from county and listed as a Kelpie mix but we think she looks a bit like a shepherd mix too maybe. Her momma is about 35 lbs so if we had to guess, we'd say she'll end up around a medium size pup when full grown. Flower is a petite girl and is always exploring. She's so curious of everything around her - it's fun to watch experience all the new things. She's happy go lucky and when you call her name, she doesn't just run to you, she does a little prance/hop and it's got to be one of the cutest things ever!

Flower will be tentatively available for adoption on Wednesday, 1/27, on our website under Adoptions Uncrated at 7pm.

animal.description:
Breed: Bloodhound mix
Sex: Female
DOB: ~01/22/2019
Weight: 91 lbs
Energy Level: Low-Medium
Personality Type: Affectionate, Quiet, Mellow, Sweet
History: Transferred from another shelter
Good With: Dogs, Kids
Ideal Home: Any home ready for a giant lap dog! Apartments not recommended.
Fence Requirements: Preferred.
Special Info: Shera likes to jump up and give hugs!

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Jimmy now goes by the name Benny and is a 1 year old Jack Russell mix. He was adopted when he was a baby and is being returned due to no fault of his own. His family had a new baby and they feel that they are now unable to give Benny the love and attention that he deserves. He has been trained by Smart Dog School and is a graduate. Hes crate trained and potty trained. We think he would be best in a house with an active mom/dad. Or a house with other active dogs that he can run and play with. He loves being outside and playing. He is crate trained and used to sleeping in his crate at night. He is energetic and active and good with kids, cats and dogs.

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting this baby, please fill out an application. They currently are fixed, up to date on shots, wormings, preventatives and are microchipped. Adoption fee is $188 ($175 Adoption Fee + $13 Lifetime Registration Fee for Microchip), applications can be filled out at this link. https://www.petstablished.com/adoption_form/10167/generic .We cannot guarantee breed or size when full grown.

Due to our current situation, with more great applicants than we have available puppies and young adults, we are no longer accepting applications from people that are over 150 miles away. Exceptions will be made on dogs over the age of 3, special needs dogs and direct referrals from our volunteers.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Bailey. I am a super sweet, loving, smart and extremely playful 9 month old Australian Shepherd/Border Collie mix with the energy of a true Border Collie. I am looking for a forever home with a human who is as active as me and has Border Collie/Australian Shepherd experience as well as a comfortable bed that I can sleep on at night. I am potty trained and know how to sit and wait for my dinner. I also do well in my crate. I would love to go running with my forever family or even complete in agility. Some of my favorite activities include hiking, playing with stuffed animals and playing even more. I get along with other dogs. I also get along with kids but I am so active and playful I would do better in a home with older kids and adults who understand my breed. I need someone committed to providing positive based training for a puppy like me with a LOT of energy and a habit of using my mouth too much. I would probably do best in a home that isnt very stressful and chaotic as I will pick up on that energy and become overexcited. 

 

Please keep in mind that I am a young HERDING BREED; I still require correction for my mouthiness and do need an owner that understands my inherent instincts. 

*Homeownership Required!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

animal.description:
This beautiful beagle mix pair will be traveling to Seattle in search of 
a home and will only be placed together, not as a single beagle. Alfie and Amber were born in a “kill pound” in South Korea in 2017. Sadly, their mother died giving birth. The babies came to the attention of Beagle Rescue Network and were moved to their safe shelter. The third pup was adopted, but Amber and Alfie have never had adopter interest and have no chance of finding a home in Korea. 
They are both friendly with people and love attention. We don’t know about cats so they probably should have a no cat home. Amber and Alfie have not had experience with children and would be best in a home with older children or no children. They are larger than most beagles and  are both overweight at almost 50 pounds but with a fenced yard for play and lots of walks, they will lose those extra pounds. They are currently in a foster home in Korea waiting for flight arrangements.
Alfie will need surgery for a luxating patella. Seattle Beagle Rescue will cover the surgery costs. If you have a place in your heart and home for Amber and Alfie, the adoption link is below. 
www.beaglerescue.org/adoption-form

Picture of pups was from 2017 showing the litter of 3.  The trip-colored beagle was their mom.  

Alfie and Amber are available and the adoption fee is $400 for the pair. If you are interested in him or any of the beagles available through Seattle Beagle Rescue, the first step is to fill out our adoption form at https://www.beaglerescue.org/adoption-process-1 and tell us a little bit about yourself. 

All of our dogs are in foster homes as we do not have a shelter. We are in desperate need of foster homes. We are having to turn down dogs that need us for a lack of foster homes. If you live in a house, have children that are at least school age, and want to give a temporary home to a desperate dog, please fill out our foster home application. https://www.beaglerescue.org/foster-form You will make a needy beagle very happy.

animal.description:
Hello! I’m so happy to meet you! I love, LOVE life, and there is so much still to learn. My foster home is great — I have a canine brother, two feline sisters, lots of comfy dog beds, and a Kong toy I just love. I happily keep myself busy with it until I get tired and have a little nap. Here’s a thing I can’t quite figure out – my legs are kind of wobbly, and I have no reflex on my paws. I’m not sure why but the humans around me are talking lots about it and saying that I’m gonna have to get some tests done. I’m not too bothered by it and can still run and enjoy exploring and playing, but stairs are something I cannot handle by myself. Hopefully the tests will help figure me out, and then I will let you know straight away. Nonetheless, I’m ready anytime if you want to meet me. I’d certainly love to meet you and show you what a happy, loving and gentle pup I am.

If you are interested in meeting this pooch, please download the Adoption Questionnaire (farescue.org/pdf_files/questionnaire_canine.pdf), fill it out and email it back to us at info@farescue.org or fax (310) 362-0321. You can also meet this and/or other available dogs at our weekend adoptions.

animal.description: Introducing Lasha, a gorgeous, sweet 4-year-old, housetrained Lab, Retriever mix. Lasha lives in a foster home and does not see many dogs on her walks. However, she is friendly and curious with the dogs she meets and would probably do well in a home with other dogs. Lasha is new to her foster family and hasn't been left alone as of yet, but she is fine at night when left on the dog bed. Lasha has not been in a crate, but loves her spot in the bed and will not roam around the house. She is a well-behaved girl and very well-mannered. She has been free to roam at night in the living room, but rarely leaves her spot. She's a very quiet dog and she would likely be fine on her own while you're out and about running your errands. Lasha is the sweetest girl! She loves attention and back scratches and will give you kisses if you let her. She is very interested in other people and pets outside of her foster home. She lives in a high traffic area so she gets a little distracted by all the surroundings, but generally does well. She is heartworm positive, but all that means is that she will need a couple months of rest while she is being treated at APAs! Expense, and after that she will be as good as new. Lasha is not a fan of elevators, and would prefer a home on the ground floor or one that is accessible by stairs. Lasha is great on a leash and is non-reactive to the sights and sounds of the downtown area where she lives. She listens well and stops at the curbs before crossing the street. She is also very playful and loves to run. She gets interested and excited when encountering another runner, biker, or dog, but is able to keep moving and is polite and respectful. Lasha enjoys snoozing on her bed, eating a big meal, going outside for morning and night time walks and/or runs. She LOVES going out for walks and running on the path outside of her foster home. Lasha is easy going and would fit well in most homes, with the exception of ones with lots of stairs and elevators. She would do well in a home or an apartment as she is not a barker, and she would enjoy a home where she gets regular walks or runs, but is very mellow and quiet and will curl up on her bed when she is not being active. Would you like to take walks with this sweet good-natured girl? Come meet Lasha today!

animal.description:
If you are reading this post and has the heart for a senior dog like me to adopt, 
just so you know consider me. 
Here is my story:
My name is Gypsy Lou and I am 10 years old. I was surrendered in the shelter due to severe tooth abscess in both side, my cheeks were swollen, oozing with pus caused by ulceration. I was very painful and my mouth has had foul odor that makes an entire room stink/smell so bad. My owner was suffering of dementia, lost his home and can no longer take care of me. Today, I am fully vetted and healthy, my dental treatment done and resolved, I don't stink anymore, I'm up to date with all my shots, microchipped and spayed. Just like a puppy, I have so much love to give and because of what I've been through I am forever grateful to anyone who will adopt and love me. I am perfect to anyone who needs a loyal companion. I love to sit next to my humans while relaxing, watching TV or listening to music, I can be playful at times if I want to, I like  the car rides as well, walk on a leash, sit on your lap, snuggle or cuddle.

animal.description:
This adorable boy is Loki, a 9 year old, male Hound mix - possibly Vizsla - who currently weighs about 35 pounds. He was starved prior to rescue so he's been steadily gaining weight. Loki is not only handsome, he is such a happy, joy-filled, easy going dog whose tail never stops wagging. Loki will follow you around just to be sure you know he's there. He likes cuddling and getting his belly scratched, but is also independent enough where he enjoys some alone time. Loki gets along with every person he meets and gets along with most other dogs; he has been very passive with the other dog in his foster home.

Loki absolutely loves going for his long afternoon walks, helping his foster mom reach her 10,000 steps a day on the Fitbit. He definitely needs an active family that loves to play and walk him. We would also like him to have another gentle dog in the home as he loves the companionship of them; Loki doesn't like it when other dogs get in his face. Loki would do best with a 6ft privacy fence because he can be an escape artist. He is a great dog and will make a wonderful family companion. Loki is housebroken, has great home manners, and is crate trained. He is approved for households with children 10 years and older.

This dog has been examined by a licensed veterinarian, provided inoculations, been neutered, tested for heartworm disease (negative) and placed on monthly preventative, plus microchipped. In addition, we ran a blood panel to check for overall health and Loki has no concerning health issues; he's doing great! ADOPTION APPLICATIONS are available by request directly through email - acaringplace@comcast.net Please do NOT use our website's online application since it is not working properly. A Caring Place - All Breed Dog Rescue adopts throughout the Greater Chicagoland Area. All dogs and puppies live in foster homes, providing you as the adopter, with information on the animal's behaviors, needs, and requirements. We are always in search of fosters care providers. If you are one of those special people willing to open your heart and home to an animal in need and would like to receive information on how you can foster an animal, please contact us.

animal.description:
Bonded Pair!
Sayde and Oz are 5-6 years old and weigh 30-35 pounds each. Oz is the male, he is deaf, very loving and cautious. He was attached to me from the beginning (his foster) and will be an excellent companion. Sayde is the female and is blind in one eye. The vet believes it is from an old eye injury that was not taken care of. She is also very loving and snuggly. They have adapted to living in doors but we think that they were mostly outdoor dogs, they did not know how to use the stairs or what a glass door was. They are great walkers and will be excellent for a family without other dogs. They are bonded and believe to be siblings. Their adoption fee is $295 each and covers the cost of their spay/neuter, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), microchips and microchip registrations.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for he/she. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We do not hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog, please visit our website to complete an adoption application. It is in the ADOPTION folder at the top of our home page. Just fill in the blanks and SEND.
We commonly receive multiple applications for a single dog. Nevertheless, only one applicant will be invited to meet a dog on Saturday at Petsmart in Yorba Linda between noon and 3 pm OR on a mutually agreeable day, time and place during the week.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $295-$495.

Sweet little Abba has done QUITE the turnaround from the terribly scared, shaking girl we picked up a few days ago! She is an absolute LOVE - she has lots of energy and loves her food (especially chicken!).

She is a GREAT walker! She keeps a brisk pace and can go a good distance, she can even take stairs on her own - up and down. She also loves to sit in our laps. She is housebroken and doesn't bark (am I describing a dream dog, or what?) She will whimper softly to get our attention, some loving rubs calms her right down. She seems to be a dog who wants/needs a lot of companionship and in return, she'll be a sweet and loving companion,

animal.description:
Meet Bounce!

13-year-old Bounce came to us from Orange County Shelter on December 3rd. He weighs 21 lbs. Bounce had two delicate surgeries in December to correct a perineal hernia. Our vet had to made it a two-part surgery, because Bounce had so many organs stuck in his hernia! We are so thankful this resilient little guy has recovered from both surgeries and is feeling great!

Bounce can be reserved in the play yard with all the other little dogs and will not be the first to greet you, which can cause him to be overlooked by potential adopters. However, away from all the hustle bustle of the play yard, his cute personality begins to emerge! Volunteers recently took him to Liberty Station in San Diego and as soon as Bounce's little feet touched the ground, his face lit up, and he was so happy to walk. They reported that he walks so well - lightly and loosely (with slack) on leash. As you can see in the video, Bounce literally bounces!

Bounce rides perfectly in the car, looking out the window and napping. He is very gentle when taking treats and politely sits while people are eating. He gets along with other dogs, both at FFF and when he went on the outing.

Bounce is ready for a Forever Family! Apply here to meet him: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm. CANCELLED UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE DUE TO COVID-19

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 1/18/21 KG

This cutie is a 8 month old Husky & American Staffordshire Terrier Mix  who weighs approximately 30 lbs and still growing! Choco is house trained and crate trained. 

Choco is full of puppy love and energy! He loves to play and does well with other dogs, although like most puppies he still needs to be corrected and continue to learn how to have good play manners. Choco tends to form strong bonds with his female caregiver and can be slow to trust men. He will need a home that will continue to work on introducing him to knew people and continue to properly socialize and train him. He may do best in a single person home or with a couple. Choco would love to have a playful furry sibling who can teach him all about being a confident dog. He will also need continued training and structure to thrive. He is very intelligent which will be a huge asset for further training but like most working dogs he will need continued enrichment to stay stimulated and out of trouble! 

If you’re interested in adopting Choco fill out an application today!

animal.description:
Dudley is an Italian Greyhound/Jack Russell mix estimated at 2 years old. Dudley MUST have a 6 ft privacy fence and a home with no children under the age of 10.

An apartment will NOT work for him. He also requires a family that will work with him and be patient and understanding of his separation anxiety. When he is comfortable with someone, Dudley is a happy, loving boy who snuggles as close as possible and gives sweet kisses.

Like a typical Jack Russell, he has a lot of energy and would love a home that takes him on long, daily walks. Dudley is very smart and needs mental stimulation with training and playing.

He was known to dig out of his previous home's fence and can easily clear a shorter fence and baby gate, which is one reason why he requires a privacy fence. If he sees a squirrel, he WILL do everything he can to get to it. Dudley is very skittish of new people and sounds and is an extreme flight risk, darting through a door faster than you can blink. He needs a secure harness and/or collar when on walks or in an unfenced area because he will suddenly back up or try to run if he's startled by a person or sound. Another reason a fence is required is that his potty habits would likely significantly decline without a fence, especially in bad weather. He relies on the fast, easy access to the yard to be successful at this point.

Dudley is working on his potty habits and does pretty well when taken out regularly.

Like most Italian greyhounds, however, he does not like bad weather, so needs extra encouragement to go on those days. His foster parents are keeping a belly band on him when he cannot be monitored as he has shown some marking behavior. Dudley loves to eat and loves to eat other dogs' food if given the chance, so he needs to be fed separately.

After a couple weeks with his foster family, Dudley now sleeps quietly in his crate through the night, as long as the crate is in the room with the family.

However, Dudley cannot be crated when his foster family has to leave for work or errands, as he will panic and destroy the crate, even risking his safety.

Dudley is a loving, friendly, active dog who needs a special home to help him thrive. An adopter with Jack Russell Terrier and Italian Greyhound breed experience is preferred. He cannot go to a home that will be gone long hours, and especially a home that will be transitioning from working at home to working at the office as a result of the pandemic, as this would be extremely stressful for him.

Dudley has been neutered and is up-to-date on his immunizations.

Out-of-state applications are not being considered at this time.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Hachi's family loved her but having a German Shepherd puppy requires

consistency in training or the puppy grows up to a canine version of a " wild child "........and this describes Hachi !

Hachi is very sweet and affectionate BUT has zero impulse control or basic good manners :-) ASR volunteers are working with her teaching her not to jump and to walk nicely on a leash but she's a true diamond in the rough.

We absolutely love working with this exuberant happy gal and know that she will make some lucky adopter a wonderful companion !

She has lived with children but due to her jumping , she may inadvertently knock over smaller children, we recommend over 12 years.

**When applying to adopt one of our puppies, please remember this: Up to the age of 8 months old, puppies cannot be left alone for a standard work day.

Arrangements will have to be in place for 4 hour intervals until the pups are at least 8 months old. Having someone with them every 4 hours until they are older greatly facilitates the housebreaking process

If you are not yet approved to adopt from All Shepherd Rescue, please fill out our online application at www.allshepherdrescue.com. Our adoption fee is $300.00.

animal.description:
The Golden Girls Allie and Cora

Meet Allie and Cora, transplants all the way from Mississippi. 

Allie and Cora are approximately five and a half to six months old. They were found along with their mother Pearl (adopted by Mississippi foster mom) a black lab, starving on a backwoods Road in Northeast mississippi.

Allie and Cora spent two and a half months in their Mississippi foster home gaining weight and being showered with love and attention, something they never had. *Side note, foster mom moved to Mississippi 11 months ago from north West Indiana and has been involved in animal welfare and rescue for 33 years, which is why these girls were sent up north. Sadly, there is a HUGE amount of abandoned, abused, neglected and starved dogs down south thrown away like trash. 

The girls now reside until adopted, with our founder, Jean.

The Golden Girls are Facebook famous! Their foster mom shared their photo taken with the neighborhood UPS man on the Facebook page "UPS dogs" garnering over 16,000 likes/loves in just under an hour.

Mom is a black lab. Dad appeared to be a retriever/hound mix. Physically, Allie takes more after the lab/hound side, whereas Cora takes after the lab/retriever side.

Allie is outgoing and bold. Cora is more shy, reserved and whines when excited. Both love people and other dogs and are very good watch dogs, even at their young age. The girls are very rambunctious puppies who love one another very much. Though very bonded and our wish is for them to be adopted together, they can be separated.

They both need more leash training and obedience school would do wonders for any new puppy or dog. The girls are crate trained, working on house potty training and do great on a schedule as their Mississippi foster home operated on a schedule. They lived with multiple dogs of all sizes, breeds and ages. They were submissive and if they became over rambunctious and an adult dog corrected them, they respected the correction, especially their mom's. 

Our adoptable pets must live INSIDE the HOME as part of the family!

The girls are current on all vaccinations including rabies, Spayed, dewormed and microchipped. Their adoption fee is $350 for a single adoption or $500 if you adopt the pair.

Please email Jean at cryforhelprescue@gmail.com to inquire. A completed adoption application and excellent vet references for past and current pets required before a meet and greet will be considered. A home visit is required for any adoption and can be done during the meet and greet for an approved applicant.

There are 6 girls:
Bailey Blossom Belle 
Amber Annie Apple

And 4 boys
Baxter Archer Axel Atticus

Our adoption fee is $750 and includes three rounds of puppy vaccines, and having them fixed and microchipped around 6 months old.

Please download an application from our website, or shoot us an email to apply.

Thanks!

animal.description:
SWEET KANDI - FOSTER TO ADOPT PROGRAM

At this time we are seeking out a foster to adopt home as Kandi is NOT ready for adoption.  Kandi will require 2 separate orthopedic surgeries to repair her cruciate ligaments.  She will be in foster care for a period of at least one year as she will need to be medically cleared for adoption as well as be fully vetted through the rescue.

Kandi is a very sweet 11 month old Chocolate Labrador Retriever.  She is currently overweight and will need to lose approximately 15 pounds.  Her current weight is 80 pounds and she should be approximately 65 pounds.

We are looking for a serious foster, with the intention once she is medically cleared, to adopt home.

Her home should be a quiet home as she will require crate rest and to be kept low key.  There will be a rehabilitation plan for each surgery that the foster to adopt must follow.  This includes specific rehabilitation exercises to be done at home in a specific time period.

The foster to adopt must be willing to take her to her follow up appointments as well as taking her to and from her second surgery.

We are looking for a home that is within a 1/2 hour radius of the Hamilton area.  The main vet is located in the Hamilton, Ontario area and the orthopedic vet is located in Etobicoke.  

A fenced in secure yard is a must.

We are looking for a foster to adopt home where Kandi is not left alone for long periods of time.

Must be 25 years or older.

A home where there is not a lot of stairs is a requirement as Kandi will not initially be able to do stairs.

If you are interested in becoming Kandi's foster to adopt home please send us an email at deannaaarfrescue@yahoo.ca and tell us a bit about yourself and why you would be a suitable fit for her.

We will not respond to emails that are asking if she is still available.  If the petfinder post is up we are still looking for a suitable foster to adopt home.

animal.description:
Meet Lady, a 2-year-old Golden Retriever mix spayed female.  She is good with other dogs, very playful, and mellow.  She is inseparable from her soulmate Tramp.  Our Rescue Coordinator tells us:
"Lady and Tramp are a bonded pair.  They have been through so much together, including having Archie, Betty and Veronica -- the three puppies we adopted out in December!  (Some of you may remember them!)  This sweet couple are now both healthy and ready for their Fur-Ever Home."

If you'd like to learn more about Tramp , please first fill out and send us an Adoption Application Form.  This greatly helps us in determining the best fit for this animal.  We must have this information before we can proceed further.  If it looks like you and Tramp  might be a good match, we will link you up with his Foster Family for more information and/or to arrange a meet-and-greet.

(Our Adoption Application Form is on our website at www.fur-ever-home.org, or you can get to it by clicking the "More About Fur-Ever Home" button on this page, then clicking the "Adoption Application" button that appears.)

Our compact little girl Latte is now available for adoption!

Latte has been in a foster home for about a month now and they have been able to see her blossom! She's around a year old and a perfect 36 pounds. Latte does well in the house, is crate trained, and loves her people. She will give you endless love - she's also fostered with a male pitty whom she gets along great with. She would love a forever home that provides her with lots of structure and continues to help build her confidence.

If you are interested in adopting Latte, please read our strong breed adoption requirements.

Pit bull & strong breed adoption criteria
- Must be over 25 years of age to adopt a Pit Bull, Pit Bull mix, or strong breed dog.
- Written landlord permission or a pet policy allowing the specific breed is required for adoption approval.
- A virtual home visit may be required.
- Training or breed experience is required as part of the adoption.
- Agree to not take the dog to dog parks or dog daycare.

If you are interested in meeting please fill out an application at our website www.gobeyondrescue.org/adopt. Our adoption fee is $350 and includes spay/neuter, microchipping and up to date vaccines. We Adopt in the SF Bay Area Only.

animal.description:
Meet this sweet, 3 year old girl named Angela! Angela came into the shelter with her partner-in-crime, Forest. They were both found wondering the streets and found themselves in our shelter on 1/26. Angela has a chip, but the owners did not come to the shelter to pick them up. These two are very sweet and loving dogs; all they want to do is play and soak up all the attention! Angela and Forest are calm and easy-going dogs. They both know their simple commands, so with a little TLC and time, they can learn more tricks, manners, and develop that beautiful family bond! Although Angela and Forest would love to stay together, they will also be very happy in separate, loving homes. Stop by the shelter to meet and fall in love with Angela in run 79. Her ID number is 627048. Angela is up-to-date on vaccines, microchipped, and spayed. She will be heart worm tested upon adoption. Angela can't wait to start loving her new family with all 45 pounds of her being! Please see Forest's profile for more information.

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

animal.description:
Bubba is a sweet and curious little dog who was surrendered to the rescue by his owners. They stated they did not have the time to train him. He is such a good boy I can not imagine having to give up a dog like him. He is easy to be around, not a barker and really pretty quiet. Bubba is playful and fun to be around. He can be a bit shy until he gets to know you. He loves toys, wrestling with other dogs and going for walks. And treats of course! Bubba still has some puppyish habits and will tear up tissue paper etc on the floor so he does need to be watched. He is "close" to housetrained but his owners admitted they were inconsistent with him. Bubba is a bit too curious about cats and would probably do best living in a cat free home. We have not had him around kids much but he overall has such a nice temperament that he should be ok at least with older kids. Bubba's ideal home would be in a home as an only dog. He could also be in a home with one dog but he is initially fearful of new dogs. This can sometimes lead to being a little too aggressive with them. He was in a home as an only dog and is just learning proper etiquette around other dogs. 

Bubba is a coated breed (hair grows continuously) so he will require professional grooming every 6-8 weeks. 

Bubba's adoption fee is $450

This fee includes at least one health exam at our veterinarian while in our care, altering, all vaccinations including rabies (as permitted by age), a pre-adoption professional grooming and a microchip with lifetime membership that never will cost you a fee. 
 All dogs also leave with a new collar and or harness and leash as well as a gift bag which includes among other things, a starter bag of the quality kibble that is being fed at the rescue.
Adoption fees also allow us the ability to put funds towards the next homeless or unwanted dog in need of rescue!

If you'd like to considered to for this adoption or any of our amazing rescues, please fill our the application with the help of this link. https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/AZST/Dog.

We review each application carefully. Please understand that sometimes we get numerous applications for particular dogs and as a volunteer based rescue we do not always have the time to respond to each and every one. We do our best to choose the most suitable home for each dog based on their specific personality and needs. 

Due to Covid, we are very short handed and may not contact you for up to a week to set up a meet and greet if your application is chosen. We appreciate all applicants and do our best to pair ever dog and family for a successful and happy life.

animal.description:
Midnight is one of the more interesting dogs we have come across in rescue. He is essentially a Mini Doodle of sorts. His original owners purchased him and his brother from an unscrupulous breeder. He and his brother were sold to their owners as "Maltipoo's" which is a combination of Maltese and Poodle. The owner's wanted two littermates who would not exceed 10 lbs and that is what they were told they were getting. It quickly became apparent that the dogs, particularly Midnight, were growing at an alarming rate! The owner's decided to send in the DNA of both dogs to have them tested to see what breeds they truly were. As it turns out, they were not even brothers and neither dog had Maltese or Poodle in them! Nevertheless, Midnight is a delightful boy who they decided to give up while he was still young since he was going to be WAY too big for them. Midnight is a combination of over 18 breeds according to his DNA. He ranges from a variety of large breeds like German Shepherd (16%) and Old English Sheepdog 12% to an array of small breeds like Pomeranian (10%) and Silky Terrier (8%). While we have NO idea how this came to be, he is a remarkable, adorable, funny, plunky puppy just waiting for the perfect home. We estimate he will be around 35-40 lbs although he has proven FULL of surprises. This is a fair estimate based on his weight of around 25 lbs at 4 1/2 months. 

Midnight is a coated breed (hair grows continuously) so he will require professional grooming periodically. He may shed minimally. 

Midnight is not completely housetrained but does not potty in his crate and holds it all night. 
With some consistency and persistence he should be easy to completely housetrain. 

Midnight's adoption fee is $650

This fee includes at least one health exam at our veterinarian while in our care, altering, all vaccinations including rabies (as permitted by age), a pre-adoption professional grooming and a microchip with lifetime membership that never will cost you a fee. 
 All dogs also leave with a new collar and or harness and leash as well as a gift bag which includes among other things, a starter bag of the quality kibble that is being fed at the rescue.
Adoption fees also allow us the ability to put funds towards the next homeless or unwanted dog in need of rescue!

If you'd like to considered to for this adoption or any of our amazing rescues, please fill our the application with the help of this link. https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/AZST/Dog.

We review each application carefully. Please understand that sometimes we get numerous applications for particular dogs and as a volunteer based rescue we do not always have the time to respond to each and every one. animal.description:
Cinder's is an adorable Chihuahua who came from a hoarding situation. She is very sweet and fairly outgoing which is a bit surprising given her background. She arrived with very little training but she is a very smart girl and eager to please. She is not as fearful or nervous as many Chihuahuas and she is not at all barky. Cinder's is approximately 1 1/2 years old and weighs about 7 lbs. She has striking marking that make her very unique. Cinder's is learning to walk on the leash and she rides well in the car. She gets along with all of the other dogs, seems fine with cats and seems to like everybody. She is a bit shy meeting new people but will warm up quickly. Cinders would love a family of her own, perhaps with another dog her size or maybe with older children. She has some catching up to do in the LOVE department! 

Cinders is a short haired breed and will require some brushing and regular nail trims. 

Like many of the dogs in rescue, we do not know how well house trained Cinders is but she does not ever potty in her crate and waits to go outside. Some patience and consistency taking her out with you and giving her lots of praise will go a long way with this sweet girl.

"Lady and Tramp are a bonded pair.  They have been through so much together, including having Archie, Betty and Veronica -- the three puppies we adopted out in December!  (Some of you may remember them!)  This sweet couple are now both healthy and ready for their Fur-Ever Home."

If you'd like to learn more about Tramp, please first fill out and send us an Adoption Application Form.  This greatly helps us in determining the best fit for this animal.  We must have this information before we can proceed further.  If it looks like you and Tramp  might be a good match, we will link you up with his Foster Family for more information and/or to arrange a meet-and-greet.

(Our Adoption Application Form is on our website at www.fur-ever-home.org, or you can get to it by clicking the "More About Fur-Ever Home" button on this page, then clicking the "Adoption Application" button that appears.)

animal.description:
These cuties are German Shepherd/Rhodesian ridgeback puppies who were born on 12/21/20. They’re about 5 lbs currently and expected to be in the medium to large size range when full grown. These little celebrities are good with other dogs, kids and cats. They’re in foster homes working of house training and their puppy manners. These puppies will be ready for their furever homes next week (week of 2/7), but we are now accepting applications.

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for puppies covers initial deworming,  puppy vaccinations, microchip, and spay/neuter at the rescue's approved vet at 6 months of age. Please see our website for more information.

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Meet this sweet, 3 year old boy named Forest! Forest came into the shelter with his partner-in-crime, Angela. They were both found wondering the streets and found themselves in our shelter on 1/26. Angela has a chip, but the owners did not come to the shelter to pick them up. These two are very sweet and loving dogs; all they want to do is play and soak up all the attention! Forest and Angela are calm and easy-going dogs. They both know their simple commands, so with a little TLC and time, they can learn more tricks, manners, and develop that beautiful family bond! Although Forest and Angela would love to stay together, they will also be very happy in separate, loving homes. Stop by the shelter to meet and fall in love with Forest in run 79. His ID number is 627047. Forest is up-to-date on vaccines, and he will be neutered, microchipped, and heart worm tested upon adoption. Forest can't wait to start loving his new family with all 55 pounds of his being! Please see Angela's profile for more information.

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

These puppies will be ready for their furever homes next week (week of 2/7), but we are now accepting applications.

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for puppies covers initial deworming,  puppy vaccinations, microchip, and spay/neuter at the rescue's approved vet at 6 months of age. Please see our website for more information.

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

*Any breed labels used by Take Paws Rescue, its employees/volunteers, or on vet records provided cannot be guaranteed.  Breed labels are given based on information obtained during intake and/or best guesses based on appearance and/or temperament of the dogs and Take Paws Rescue gives no assurance to the accuracy of these labels. Labels are necessary for postings to many animal networking sites, such as Pet Finder, and are no way a guarantee. Additionally, exact age and potential size cannot be guaranteed.

animal.description:
Timber is a SWEET 1-2 yr old, 50 lb pittie mix. He is fluffy and soft like velvet. He is in the submissive side and willing to follow the lead. He would be great in any household, he’s housebroken and as gentle as they come. He loves to curl up on your lap and ‘purr’ when you scratch his head. Timber is such a beautiful gray color with light eyes, pictures so nor do him justice!

Adopters must live within a 100-mile radius of Joliet, IL to be considered. The adoption fee is $425. This covers all shots, spay/neutering and microchip.

To be considered for this dog. Please fill out an application here: https://www.pawsup4rescue.org/dog-cat-applicaiton

Our adoption process typically takes from one to two weeks. When you find an animal you are interested in, we ask that you fill out an application as a first step so we can determine if your family is a good fit for the animal. If you are, then we will contact you to arrange a time for you and your family to meet the animal so you can decide if it is a good fit. If you currently have dogs, we require that the dogs be present at the meeting to make sure it's a good fit all around. Once compatibility is determined, we move on to the paperwork and finalizing the adoption. 

If the meet is not a good fit, we will keep your application on file for up to 1 year and we will gladly consider your family for another dog. 

Follow us on FACEBOOK: www.Facebook.com/PawsUp4Rescue/ 
and on INSTAGRAM: www.Instagram.com/Paws_Up_4_Rescue/

animal.description:
Say hello to your new best friend!

Billie is a very young Anatolian Shepard/Husky mix. Billie is a little shy and very playful. She is one pup from a litter of 9 to their husky mom. 

Billie's mama produced a few litters for her caretakers before being dumped and left to fend for herself. Her rescuer discovered she was expecting before they could get her spayed and asked POPP for help. Mama (Luna) and all her pups have been well cared for and are now ready to start lives with their furever families. 

Both Huskies and Anatolian Shepherds have some unique breed traits so we are looking for people familiar with the breeds. 

If you are interested in adopting Billie, her adoption fee is $200. She will be spayed, microchipped and vaccines started. Here is a link to our adoption questionnaire: https://www.popptricities.org/adopt/adoption-questionnaire-canine/

animal.description:
Sunny had a family for the first year of her life, then the family decided they didn't want to have a dog, therefore they relinquished her to DRWB.

Since then Sunny came to live with a loving foster that has other dogs.

Sunny can be shy initially when she first meet strangers, she is very afraid of the broom; she was probably not treated very well; it takes only a couple of days for her to feel comfy once she realizes that her new human is a good person.

Sunny deserves a chance to have a forever loving family to call her own, she is a sweet.

Potty training is in progress and she is learning fast.

We are looking for the best family for sunny, with a lot of love and a little patience to gain her trust.

animal.description:
Info coming soon!  In the mean time he is looking for a sponsor.

Missy’s Haven is going to take good care of me.  They have me scheduled for treatment at the end of July, and by the end of August I should be ready for my very own home.  

In the mean time, if you would like to learn more about me just let them know.  I’m available for foster while I go through my treatment.  Find out more about fostering at http://missyshavencr.org.  This should be just about 30 days.  Who knows you may just fall in love!

MISSYS HAVEN CANINE Rescue, in San Antonio TX, does not have a shelter - ALL of our dogs are raised in foster homes in the San Antonio area. Each dog comes spayed or neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations that are appropriate for their age, microchipped, heartworm tested and on current on monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventative. 

ALL OF THIS IS INCLUDED IN THE ADOPTION FEE OF $200.00 FOR LOCAL DOGS AND $250.00 FOR PUPPIES. ( Local is in the state of Texas)! Medical records will come with each dog at the time of adoption.

IF THIS IS AN OUT OF STATE ADOPTION, TRANSPORT TO YOU is included in the adoption fee of $400.00 for adult dogs and $500.00 for puppies. We transport all over the country!!

All our dogs are socialized and we try to provide you a good understanding of the dog’s personality. Please visit our website for more information about what we do; http://www.missyshavencr.org.  You will also find helpful our adoption application and pictures of our all our dogs/pups looking for homes!!

Don’t forget to like us at http://Facebook.com/missyshavencr
